fields.itinerary: Meet at Highland Center at 8:30. Take the Crawford path to Mt Pierce. Potentially continue to Mt Eisenhower, since the weather seems glorious.

fields.description:
Get ready to rock out in your onesie atop Mt Pierce. It's a relaxed 6 mile 2000 ft of elevation gain hike, with options to add on Eisenhower or Jackson if we are feeling super comfortable and the weather is glorious. This is an above-treeline hike and some previous winter experience is required.

And in addition to your onesie, there will be hot cocoa to help warm you up after the summit.
fields.prereqs: enthusiasm about silly hike ideas, not your first winter hike

fields.description:
Lead a trip for incoming grad students: If you're a 3-season hiking leader, we need your help to lead hikes on the Graduate Student Council (GSC) hiking trip on Saturday, Sep 3.

Every fall MITOC and the GSC organize a hiking trip as part of the orientation week for incoming grad students. The GSC charters two buses; one goes to Franconia, the other to Ferncroft. We split into groups of ~8, hike, and the leaders (this would be you) lead an easy-medium 6-8h hike.

This signup is for the 16 leaders we need to run this trip. Your responsibilities would be to lead a hike and be back to the bus by 6. You don't have to be a grad student, be MIT-affiliated, or have experience organizing large trips. MITOC and the GSC are organizing trip signups, transportation, food, emails, and all other logistics. We'll plan the hiking routes and turnaround times, and provide free breakfast and dinner for leaders. We just need you to hop on the bus, lead a hike when you get to the trailhead, and be back on time :)
fields.name: [Leaders] GSC Hiking Trip Leaders

fields.description: Paddle trip to include the Brewster Islands and possibly the Graves light, conditions permitting. The level is advanced beginner to intermediate (capable of moderate paddle pace to keep group together and general idea of basic rescue procedure). Distance of 10-12 miles with 2 stops. Both tandems and a number of singles will be used. Current MITOC membership required. Ability to dress in non-cotton required. Trip fee is $15, pay MITOC to confirm after trip leader approves Will meet at MITOC boat room area at 8:00 am.
fields.prereqs: MITOC membership, ability to swim, ability to properly dress in non-cotton for water temperature, advanced beginner to intermediate level skills

fields.description:
Come spend a weekend in New Hampshire hiking, climbing, eating, roasting marshmallows, and singing around a campfire!

### What's a Circus?

Circuses are a weekend of hiking and climbing trips based out of MITOC's Camelot cabin in Groton, NH. It's a great way to meet fellow outdoorsy folks and check out the White Mountains.

We will provide breakfast Saturday and Sunday, dinner Saturday, s'mores materials, gear rentals (sleeping bags, foam pads, climbing gear), and volunteers to lead trips on Saturday and Sunday.

### I'm interested! Now what?

**1\. Become a MITOC member if you aren't one already.** Benefits include being able to rent super-cheap gear, stay in our cabins, come on trips like this, and more. You become a member by signing a waiver and paying the annual membership fee ($15 for students, $20 for MIT affiliates, $25 for others.) You can do both [here](http://mitoc.mit.edu/#join).

**2\. Sign up for the trip on this page before midnight on Monday, September 12\.** Unlike previous circuses, signups will be done using a random lottery, so it doesn't matter whether you sign up now or right before the deadline. You will be notified whether you got a spot on Tuesday, September 13\. If you didn't get a spot, don't despair! There are usually some participants who drop off the trip, so we can often take many of the people on the waiting list.

**3\. Attend the mandatory pre-trip meeting Wednesday, September 14 at 7pm in the MITOC office (W20-461.)** We'll discuss logistics, then you can rent any gear you need. _If you're renting gear, please bring a checkbook to put down a security deposit. If you don't have checks, find a friend who does._

**4\. Pay the trip fee.** The cost is $20 for students, $30 for all others, $5 less for drivers. It covers all gear rentals (sleeping bags, pads, climbing gear, etc.), breakfast Saturday and Sunday, dinner on Saturday, cabin upkeep, and White Mountain National Forest permits. MITOC does not profit from circus trip fees. There are no refunds, so signing and paying is a commitment to join the trip. Don't pay your trip fee until you've attended the pre-trip meeting and are guaranteed a spot!

### Schedule

**Friday, September 16:** Carpool up to the cabin. It takes about 2.5 hours to get to Camelot without traffic, so most people will leave between 6 and 7 PM. Everyone should plan to be at the cabin by 10 PM, when we meet to plan hiking and climbing trips for Saturday.

**Saturday, September 17:** Hiking and climbing trips in the White Mountains! Yay! Everyone will return to the cabin Saturday night, and we'll cook dinner, roast marshmallows, and plan trips for Sunday.

**Sunday, September 18:** Clean up the cabin in the morning. More trips. You return directly to Cambridge after your Sunday trip; return time varies depending on the length of your trip.

_MITOC is not a guide service. We are an all-volunteer organization dedicated to helping the MIT community enjoy the great outdoors. Unexpected events happen. If you sign up, be prepared to be flexible!_

**Questions?** Contact circus-chair@mit.edu
